{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566448"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:41:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:41:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.74,0.05,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64892"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"937"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11282"},{"type":"tags","id":"11285"},{"type":"tags","id":"11287"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27215"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is reviewing different social media posts made by healthcare professionals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following social media posts is most inappropriate for a healthcare professional to share?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advocating for a peaceful resolution of a war or conflict","Describing a rare medical case seen that day at the local hospital","Sharing an article about public health initiatives from a reputable source","Sharing a link to new clinical practice guidelines","Promoting an upcoming community health screening event"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDescribing a rare medical case\u003C/strong\u003E seen at a local hospital is inappropriate as it constitutes a serious breach of patient confidentiality and privacy obligations. Due to the rarity of certain medical conditions, even posts that do not include explicit identifying information (like names or dates) may still allow patients to be identified by others in the community. This is particularly problematic in smaller communities or with unusual presentations. Additionally, sharing clinical details on social media may breach professional obligations and institutional policies regarding confidentiality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent appropriate and professional use of social media:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvocating for a peaceful resolution of a war or conflict\u003C/strong\u003E is acceptable professional conduct as it represents engagement with humanitarian issues without compromising professional standards or patient care. This is acceptable according to the National Board guidelines as it does not present risks to public safety, does not risk public confidence in the profession, and does not require action to maintain professional standards.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing an article about public health initiatives\u003C/strong\u003E from reputable sources helps educate the public and promotes evidence-based health information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing a link to new clinical practice guidelines\u003C/strong\u003E facilitates professional development and knowledge sharing among healthcare workers, improving quality of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting an upcoming community health screening event\u003C/strong\u003E supports public health outreach and preventive healthcare initiatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare professionals must carefully consider their social media presence as it reflects on their professional identity and the broader healthcare profession. Key principles include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENever sharing identifiable patient information or cases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintaining professional boundaries with patients and colleagues\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESharing only evidence-based health information from reliable sources\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing social media to promote public health and education in an ethical manner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare professionals must maintain patient confidentiality when using social media, even if identifying details are not explicitly shared.","Professional boundaries between healthcare workers and patients must be maintained on social media platforms.","Social media posts by healthcare workers should never contain misleading health information or unprofessional comments about colleagues or work environments."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Social media: How to meet your obligations under the National Law [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/Codes-Guidelines-Policies/Social-media-guidance.aspx.","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64892"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64892"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T10:04:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T10:09:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"